United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"'Lame","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of German   Lahm  .","French (<b>Lamé</b>): nickname from Old French <i>amé</i> ‘beloved’ (from the past participle of <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’), with fused definite article <i>l'</i>.","Albanian: from a short form of the Muslim personal name   Islam  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lahm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunther, Otto.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic):","nickname for someone who was slow or lame, from Middle High German <i>lam</i> ‘lame’."]}]},{"name":"Lord'","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Cam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Probably abbreviated from Camillus."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm Cam MacGregor -  'Lame Lord' of Glenorchy was born in 1275, in Scotland, his father, Lord Gregor MacGregor 10th Lord Lag, MacGregor, was 55 and his mother, Lady Marion de Lennox MacGregor, was 45. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Mary MacAlpin of Finnick. He died in 1374, in Bute, Scotland, at the age of 99."},"et":{"1275–1374":"1275–1374","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1310–1330":"1310–1330","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1374":"1374","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1266":"1266","1306":"1306","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Argyll, Scotland.":"Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland",", , , Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfries and Galloway, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1374":"1275–1374","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1310–1330":"1310–1330","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1374":"1374","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1266":"1266","1306":"1306","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Argyll, Scotland.":"Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland",", , , Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfries and Galloway, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1275–1374":"1275–1374","1268–Female":"1268–Décédée","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1305–Male":"1305–Décédé","1306–Female":"1306–Décédée","1310–1330":"1310–1330","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1374":"1374","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1266":"1266","1306":"1306","Glenorchy, Argyll, S